comments.body:
@vrothberg Thanks for the feedback! looking back at [the issue](https://github.com/containers/podman/issues/10108) I believe what @edsantiago wanted was, something that "nicely packaged" save/load to a remote host using ssh, into a podman command. That combined with Brent's idea to use system connection led me down this path.

It is a slightly complicated feature but I think it is a useful one. Being able to specify a remote host and image even on your own network can allow for some cool applications and integrations down the line. I think we should meet next week with @rhatdan to discuss design because there might be too much here to begin with. However, what I have currently seems to function pretty well and after some tweaks with the actual input, is pretty easy to use! 

Overall, it seems to me like we have two different ideas of what scp should be but as Dan pointed out when I first started, the `podman save/podman --remote load` version doesn't necessarily add much functionality over what we currently have.

@mtrmac I can't reply directly but in response to:

> Now we saving DestImageName, documented as “the one user desires to load”; isn’t the image we are saving a source, and “the one the user wants to copy elsewhere”?

"the image the user desires to load on their machine or elsewhere" is synonymous to "the one the user wants to copy elsewhere" I believe.
